Russian for Beginners is the continuation course of ABC II and it is meant for the students who have studied Russian for two semesters previously...We will read  and translate different texts (including dialogues). There will be discussions and exercises for integrating the vocabulary into everyday communication situations.  Grammar will be revised.
Topics
* Hobbies. Grammar: telling the time, verb conjugation, the imperative 
* My budget.  Grammar: numerals, pronouns, adverbs.
* I live in Estonia. The sights in Estonia. Grammar: the verb, comparison of adjectives.
* Let&acute;s go to Russia. Famous Russians. Grammar: verbs of movement with prefices.
* Travelling. Grammar: prefixes; conjunctions in composite sentences, witing a personal letter.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to develop the communication skills, reading skills and knowledge of grammar and vocabulary. The course revises and reinforces the skills acquired at the basic level, develops the skills in expressing oneself in oral and in written.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After finishing the course students:
- can understand the essential in a familiar topic (studies, working, free time etc.);
- can compile texts on a familiar topic or a topic interesting for the student both in the oral and written mode, and use the newly acquired grammatical structures in the right way;
- can describe experiences and plans, exchange important information and express their  opinion on practical problems;
- can find  necessary information from everyday texts (advertisements, menus, schedules) and can understand the gist of  radio and TV programmes that are broadcast slowly and clearly, if these include familiar or interesting topics;
- can participate in short conversations on everyday matters and in ordinary situations without prior preparation;
- can make social contact (greeting, saying good-bye, introduction, thanking, agreeing on a time to meet, etc.)
- can write short simple coherent texts
